I agree with the point that you make, although I think that something like this is more idiomatic Java:<p><pre><code>    boolean hasUpper(String str){
        if(str != null){
            for(char c : str.toCharArray()){
                if(Character.isUpperCase(c)){
                    return true;
                }
            }
        } 
        return false;
    }
</code></pre>
It's wordier than the Clojure example, but less than the Strawman example given in the article.<p>I'd also argue that you could claim it reads better.  To me, "Character.isUpperCase(c)" explains what it's doing better than "(some #(Character/isUpperCase %) string))"
